    <subsection xml:id="subsubsec-area-scale-factors" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
        <title>Area Scale Factors</title>
        <objectives component="outcomes">
            <introduction>
                <dl>
                    <li>
                        <title>Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                        <p>
                            2.1 Similarity and Enlargement
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                        <p>
                            Determine the area and volume scale factor of different figures and solids
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Grade Level</title>
                        <p>
                            10
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li component="lesson-plan">
                        <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                        <p>
                            40 minutes
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </dl>
            </introduction>
            <introduction component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Define area scale factor as the ratio of the area of the image to the area of the object. State that the area scale factor equals the square of the linear scale factor: <m>\text{ASF} = (\text{LSF})^2</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Calculate the area scale factor given two similar figures. Determine the area of an image or object using the relationship between linear scale factor and area scale factor. Find the linear scale factor from a given area scale factor by taking the square root.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply area scale factor to solve problems involving similar hexagons, circles, cones, parallelograms, and real-world contexts such as maps, photographs, and architectural models.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </introduction>
        </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
            <!-- Link to blurb -->
            <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

            <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
                <sidebyside>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/area-scale-factors.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/similarity-and-enlargement/step-by-step-guide_area-scale-factors.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                    </p>
                </sidebyside>
            </sbsgroup>
        </axiom>
        <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Grouping:</alert> Pairs
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Teacher Prompts:</alert>
                <ul>
                    <li><p><q>What is <m>4 \times 4</m>?</q></p></li>
                    <li><p><q>What is <m>8 \times 8</m>?</q></p></li>
                    <li><p><q>What is the ratio of the two areas?</q></p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Early Finishers:</alert> Draw a third square with side <m>12</m> cm and verify the relationship.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Exploration:</alert> If you have an Internet connection in class, show Learners <xref ref="exploration-asf"/>.
            </p>
        </axiom>


        <activity xml:id="auto_44hzz2vp">
            <introduction xml:id="auto_l1d9nriq">
                <p xml:id="auto_yf2ph9qb">
                    <alert>Work in pairs</alert>
                </p>
            </introduction>
            <task xml:id="auto_ihph8ses">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_7d8xm2w6">
                        Draw a square with a side length of <m>4</m> cm and label it as Square <m>A</m> as shown below.
                    </p>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image label="squarea">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                  % Draw the square
                            \draw[thick, fill=none] (0,0) rectangle (2,2);
                            
                            % Add labels for the sides
                            \node[below] at (1,0) {\small $4 cm$};
                            \node[left] at (0,1) {\small $4 cm$};
                            
                            % Label the center of the square as A
                            \node at (1,1) {\small A};

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_4p3939cs">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_6fwhm5bb">
                        Draw another square with a side length of <m>8</m> cm and label it as Square <m>B</m> as shown below.
                    </p>
                    <image width="50%">
                        <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                        <latex-image label="squareb">
                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                  % Draw the square
                            \draw[thick, fill=none] (0,0) rectangle (2,2);
                            
                            % Add labels for the sides
                            \node[below] at (1,0) {\small $8 cm$};
                            \node[left] at (0,1) {\small $8 cm$};
                            
                            % Label the center of the square as A
                            \node at (1,1) {\small B};

                            \end{tikzpicture}
                        </latex-image>
                        
                    </image>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_tfpbtul6">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_yp84ci35">
                        Calculate the area of Square <m>A</m> and Square <m>B</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="task-asf-1">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_piooroue">
                        Find the ratio of the areas by dividing the area of Square <m>B</m> by the area of Square <m>A</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_rd3o2hl7">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_gyuyezlw">
                        Take one side length of Square <m>B</m>, divide it by one side length of Square <m>A</m>, and then square the result.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_glyr6k12">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_fpvxpd4m">
                        Compare your answers from steps <m>(\mathbf{d})</m> and <m>(\mathbf{e})</m>. What do you notice?
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
            <task xml:id="auto_2wk8h8i8">
                <statement>
                    <p xml:id="auto_q2mfe7lz">
                        Discuss and share your findings with the rest of the class.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </task>
        </activity>
        <exploration xml:id="exploration-asf">
            <title>Trying Out Area Scale Factors</title>
        <figure xml:id="interactive-area-scale-factors">
            <caption>Interactive Exploration of Area Scale Factors</caption>
            <interactive xml:id="area-scale-factors" platform="jsxgraph" width="90%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/area-scale-factors.js">
                <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-area-scale-factors" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1" />
                <instructions xml:id="area-scale-instructions">
                    <p>
                        Use the slider <m>k</m> at the top left to change the linear scale factor of the blue parallelogram. You can also click and drag the vertices of the original yellow parallelogram (<m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, and <m>R</m>) to change its shape. 
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        Observe the dynamically calculated bases (<m>b</m> and <m>b'</m>) and perpendicular heights (<m>h</m> and <m>h'</m>). Notice how the Area Scale Factor perfectly matches the square of the linear scale factor (<m>k^2</m>) no matter how you reshape the original figure.
                    </p>
                </instructions>
            </interactive>
        </figure>
                    
            
        </exploration>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction / Explain</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <q>If <m>\text{LSF} = 3</m>, <m>\text{ASF}</m> is NOT <m>3</m> <mdash/> it is <m>9</m>.</q>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Reverse Application:</alert> <q>If <m>\text{ASF} = 25</m>, then <m>\text{LSF} = \sqrt{25} = 5</m>.</q>
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <insight>
            <p xml:id="auto_x2wdx5w6">
                Area scale factor is the ratio of the area of the image to area of the object.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_wg1ezl8b"> 
                Area scale factor is the square of linear scale factor.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Key Formulas:</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{ASF}  \amp = (\text{LSF})^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{ASF} \amp = \frac{\text{Area of Image}}{\text{Area of Object}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{LSF} \amp = \sqrt{\text{ASF}}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_pxs6g86b">
                In the Figures below, the parallelogram <m>P'Q'R'S'</m> represents the enlarged image of paralellogram <m>PQRS</m>, transformed by a scale factor of <m>2</m>.
            </p>
            <sidebyside>
            <image width="30%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="parallelogram">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \coordinate (P) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q) at (4,0);
                        \coordinate (R) at (6,3);
                        \coordinate (S) at (2,3);

                        % Draw parallelogram with yellow fill
                        \fill[yellow!80] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;
                        \draw[purple, thick] (P) -- (Q) -- (R) -- (S) -- cycle;

                        % Label vertices
                        \node[below left] at (P) {\textbf{P}};
                        \node[below right] at (Q) {\textbf{Q}};
                        \node[above right] at (R) {\textbf{R}};
                        \node[above left] at (S) {\textbf{S}};

                            % Add dimension lines
                        
                        \node[below] at (2,-0.3) {\textbf{5 cm}};
                        \node[left] at (3,1.5) {\textbf{7 cm}}; % Height label
                    ;

                        % Define the foot of the perpendicular
                        \coordinate (T) at (2,0);

                        % Draw perpendicular line from S to PQ
                        \draw[blue, thick] (S) -- (T);

                        % Label the new point
                        \node[below] at (T) {\textbf{T}};

                        % Add right-angle symbol
                        \draw (2,0.3) -- (2.3,0.3) -- (2.3,0);
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            <image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="parallelogram1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                % Define coordinates
                        \coordinate (P') at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Q') at (8,0);
                        \coordinate (R') at (12,6);
                        \coordinate (S') at (4,6);
                        \coordinate (T') at (4,0); % Foot of perpendicular

                        % Draw parallelogram with blue fill
                        \fill[blue!30] (P') -- (Q') -- (R') -- (S') -- cycle;
                        \draw[blue, thick] (P') -- (Q') -- (R') -- (S') -- cycle;

                        % Label vertices with larger, bold text
                        \node[below left, scale=1.2] at (P') {\textbf{P'}};
                        \node[below right, scale=1.2] at (Q') {\textbf{Q'}};
                        \node[above right, scale=1.2] at (R') {\textbf{R'}};
                        \node[above left, scale=1.2] at (S') {\textbf{S'}};

                        % Draw perpendicular line from S to PQ
                        \draw[blue, thick, dashed] (S') -- (T');

                        % Label perpendicular foot
                        \node[below, scale=1.2] at (T') {\textbf{T}};

                        % Right-angle symbol
                        \draw[thick] (4,0.6) -- (4.6,0.6) -- (4.6,0);

                        % Dimension labels with larger text
                        \node[below, scale=1.4] at (4,-0.6) {\textbf{10 cm}};
                        \node[left, scale=1.4] at (5.8,3) {\textbf{14 cm}}; % Height label
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            </sidebyside>

            <p xml:id="auto_scxom0zr">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of a parallelogram}\amp = base \times height </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of PQRS} \amp = 5\, cm \times 7\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 35\, cm^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of P'Q'R'S'}\amp = 10\, cm \times 14\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 140\, cm^2</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area scale factor}\amp = \frac{\text{Area of the image}}{\text{area of the object}}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{\text{Area of P'Q'R'S'}}{\text{Area of PQRS}}\amp = \frac{140\, cm^2}{35\, cm^2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp = 4</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p>
                Learners work through the following problems (see worked examples below)
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_hbvxg679">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_2z7l2wth">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_vm4mtdq4">
                    A square whose area is <m>28</m> <m>cm^2</m> is given
                    an enlargement with a linear scale factor of <m>4</m>. Find the area of the image.
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_erwbhkd1">
                    <md>
                    <mrow>\text{Area scale factor}\amp = \frac{\text{Area of image}}{\text{area of object}}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Linear scale factor (L.S.F)}\amp = 4</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area scale factor(A.S.F)} \amp = (L.S.F)^2</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp =4^2 =16 </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Area of image}}{28} \amp = 16 </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area of image}\amp = 16 \times 28</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 448\, cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_138pwsie">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_jzrmcaqo">
                    Given that the ratio of the area of two circles is <m>\frac{25}{64}</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                Find the ratio of their radii
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the smaller one has a radius of <m>15</m> <m>\, cm</m>, find the radius of the larger one.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p>
                    <ol marker="(a)">
                        <li>
                            <p xml:id="auto_5yae0vop">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\text{Area scale factor } \amp = \frac{25}{64}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\text{Linear scale factor }\amp = \sqrt \frac {25}{64}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = \frac{5}{8}</mrow>
                                    <mrow>\text{Therefore the ratio of two radii}\amp = 5:8</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                                If the radius of the smaller circle is <m>15 \, cm</m>, then
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_o7332oz5">
                                <md>
                                    <mrow>\frac{\text{Radius of smaller circle}}{\text{Radius of larger circle}}\amp = \frac{5}{8}</mrow>
                                    <mrow> \frac{15}{\text{radius of larger circle}} \amp = \frac{5}{8} </mrow>
                                    <mrow>\text{radius of larger circle}\amp = \frac{(8 \times 15)}{5} </mrow>
                                    <mrow>\amp = 24\, cm</mrow>
                                </md>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

        <example xml:id="auto_9pjszzoe">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_dim9vjta">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_rrvfpblg">
                    Given that the following two hexagons below are similar, and the area of the first hexagon <m>A</m> is <m>450\, cm^2</m>, calculate the area of the second hexagon <m>B</m>.
                </p>

                <image source="hexagon.png">
                    <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                </image>
            </statement>

            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_0150tero">
                    <md>
                        <mrow>\text{Linear scale factor}\amp = \frac{9}{6}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area scale factor}\amp = (\frac{9}{6})^2=\frac{81}{36}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{\text{Area of hexagon A}}{\text{Area of hexagon B}} \amp =\frac{81}{36} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\frac{\text{450}}{\text{Area of hexagon B}} \amp =\frac{81}{36} </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Area of hexagon B}  \amp = \frac{36\times 450}{81}</mrow>
                        <mrow>\amp = 200 cm^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>

