        <exercises xml:id="exercises-area-scale-factor">

        <exercise xml:id="auto_xau286qv">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_p6yem21a">
                    The corresponding sides of two similar regular hexagons are <m>4\, cm</m> and <m>9\, cm</m> respectively.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_4rauo3cd">
                    (a).Find the ratio of their areas.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_5g35v2l6">
                    (b).Calculate the area of the larger hexagon if the area of the smaller hexagon is <m>64\, cm^2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Hexagons with sides <m>4</m> cm and <m>9</m> cm. (a) Area ratio <m>= 16:81</m>. (b) Smaller area <m>64</m> cm² <m>\Rightarrow</m> larger <m>= 324</m> cm².
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_uk1ndyhv">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_g6hgk2d2">
                    The ratio of the area of two similar cones is <m>\frac{9}{36}</m>.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_fgsp2qnx">
                    (a).Find the area of the smaller cone if the area of the bigger cone is <m>320\, m^2</m>

                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_w3t71a8r">
                   (b). Find the ratio of their base radii.
                </p>

                <p xml:id="auto_glwinihz">
                   (c). If the slanting height of the smaller cone is <m>7\, m</m>, find the slanting height of the larger cone.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Similar cones with area ratio <m>9:36</m>. (a) Bigger cone area <m>320</m> m² <m>\Rightarrow</m> smaller <m>= 80</m> m². (b) Radii ratio <m>= 1:2</m>. (c) Slant height smaller <m>= 7</m> m <m>\Rightarrow</m> larger <m>= 14</m> m.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_k9npelyl">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_xb32r9x7">
                    The length of a parallelogram is <m>15\, cm</m> and its area is <m>240\, cm^2</m>. Calculate the length of a similar parallelogram whose area is <m>375\, cm^2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Parallelogram length <m>15</m> cm, area <m>240</m> cm². Similar parallelogram area <m>375</m> cm². <m>\text{ASF} = \frac{25}{16}</m>, <m>\text{LSF} = \frac{5}{4}</m>. Length <m>= 18.75</m> cm.
                </p>
            </answer>
            
        </exercise>

        <exercise xml:id="auto_oxtwtxlm">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_j29ownbd">
                    The area of a circle is <m>49\, m^2</m> . A second circle has a radius that is <m>4</m> times the radius of the first circle. What is the area of the second circle?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Circle area <m>49</m> m². Second circle radius is <m>4</m> times the first. <m>\text{ASF} = 16</m>. Area <m>= 784</m> m².
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
            
        </exercises>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <table>
                <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
                <tabular halign="left">
                    <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                        <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                        <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line>Provide pre-drawn squares on grid paper so learners can count unit squares. Use integer scale factors first. Provide a formula card with <m>\text{ASF} = (\text{LSF})^2</m>.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line>Complete all phases as described. Include both forward and reverse problems. Use digital checkpoints for immediate feedback.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                    <row>
                        <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                        <cell>
                            <line><alert>Extended Investigation:</alert> Explore the relationship <m>\text{LSF} \rightarrow \text{ASF} \rightarrow \text{VSF}</m>. A cube with side <m>3</m> cm is enlarged with <m>\text{LSF} = 2</m>: <m>\text{VSF} = 8</m>. Map scale <m>1:25{,}000</m>, lake area <m>8</m> cm² on map <mdash/> find actual area.</line>
                        </cell>
                        <cell></cell>
                    </row>
                </tabular>
            </table>
            <paragraphs>
                <title>Extension Investigation Solution</title>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Volume Scale Factor Investigation:</alert> A cube has side <m>3</m> cm. Volume <m>= 27</m> cm³. With <m>\text{LSF} = 2</m>, new side <m>= 6</m> cm, new volume <m>= 216</m> cm³. <m>\text{VSF} = \frac{216}{27} = 8 = 2^3</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Map Problem:</alert> Scale <m>1:25{,}000</m>. Lake measures <m>8</m> cm² on map. Actual area <m>= 625{,}000{,}000 \times 8</m> cm² <m>= 50</m> hectares.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Scale Factor Table:</alert>
                        </p>
                        <table>
                            <tabular halign="center">
                                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                                    <cell>Dimension</cell>
                                    <cell>Scale Factor</cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>Length</cell>
                                    <cell><m>k</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>Area</cell>
                                    <cell><m>k^2</m></cell>
                                </row>
                                <row>
                                    <cell>Volume</cell>
                                    <cell><m>k^3</m></cell>
                                </row>
                            </tabular>
                        </table>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
                
            </paragraphs>
        </axiom>

